07334nam a22008655i 9781771122023DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97817711220237 a10.51644/97817711220232doi  a(DE-B1597)667896  a(OCoLC)1034865580  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0530002bisacsh04a304.20971qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aLandscapes and Landmarks of Canada :bReal, Imagined, (Re)Viewed /ced. by Munroe Eagles, Jane Koustas, Maeve Conrick, Caitríona Ní Chasaide. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b8 full-colour illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList Of Illustrations -- tLandscapes and Landmarks of Canada: Real, Imagined, (Re)Viewed -- tCanada: Islands, Landscapes, and Landmarks -- tScience at Service of Sublime Landscapes: Scientific Ecology and the Preservation of Canada’s Wilderness Landmarks in 1970s Quebec -- tPatriotisms of the People: Understanding the “Highway of Heroes” as a Canadian National Landmark -- tMaterial Differences: Ethnic Diversity and the Power of Things in Greater Sudbury -- tOur Home and Native Land: Invocations of the Land in the 2011 Canadian Federal Election -- tMemorializing an Imagined Past: Evangeline and the Acadian Deportation -- tTime and Space in the Nationalism of Thomas D’Arcy McGee -- tContesting Historical Space: The Campaign to Have Grosse Île Designated a National Historic Site with the Irish Dimension as Its Main Theme -- tEnvironmental Exposure: Two films “de légitime défense”: Richard Desjardins and Robert Monderie: L’erreur boréale / Forest Alert (1999) and Trou Story / The Hole Story (2011) -- tPostcolonial Territorial Landmarks within Canada’s Multiculturalism: The Myth of Virility -- tMapping the Migrant Mindscape in Gabrielle Roy: A Macro Definition of écriture migrante -- tThe Green Fields of Canada— Forgotten! A Reappraisal of Irish Traditional Music History in Canada -- tThe Contemporary Powwow in Eastern Canada: A Practice of Gathering -- tAbout The Authors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the Cultural Studies Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe image of the “land” is an ongoing trope in conceptions of Canada—from the national anthem and the flag to the symbols on coins—the land and nature remain linked to the Canadian sense of belonging and to the image of the nation abroad. Linguistic landscapes reflect the multi-faceted identities and cultural richness of the nations. Earlier portrayals of the land focused on unspoiled landscape, depicted in the paintings of the Group of Seven, for example. Contemporary notions of identity, belonging, and citizenship are established, contested, and legitimized within sites and institutions of public culture, heritage, and representation that reflect integration with the land, transforming landscape into landmarks. The Highway of Heroes originating at Canadian Forces Base Trenton in Ontario and Grosse Île and the Irish Memorial National Historic Site in Québec are examples of landmarks that transform landscape into a built environment that endeavours to respect the land while using it as a site to commemorate, celebrate, and promote Canadian identity. Similarly in literature and the arts, the creation of the built environment and the interaction among those who share it is a recurrent theme. This collection includes essays by Canadian and international scholars whose engagement with the theme stems from their disciplinary perspectives as well as from their personal and professional experience—rooted, at least partially, in their own sense of national identity and in their relationship to Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title fro